 Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":55,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas de Hibburne was born in 1260, in Newton, West Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Robert de Hyburne of Newton, was 41 and his mother, Jeane Cockburn, was 38. He married Lady Emma de Durham in 1290, in Hailes, Midlothian, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1320, in England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1260–1320":"1260–1320","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1275–1358":"1275–1358","1296–1371":"1296–1371","1300–1371":"1300–1371","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1223–Female":"1223–Surnud","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1358":"1358","1300":"1300","1223":"1223","1255":